==Trivia==
*In the comics, Peter Parker was bitten by a radioactive spider that granted him superpowers. Upon the death of his uncle, [[Ben Parker]], due to Parker's indifference, he decided to become a selfless hero.
*One of [[Tony Stark]]'s guesses as to Parker's superhero alias was "Spiderling." In the comics, this name is used by Parker's daughter, [[w:c:marvel:Anna-May Parker (Earth-18119)|Annie Parker]], on [[w:c:marvel:Earth-18119|Earth-18119]].
*Parker's date of birth being August 10th is a reference to ''[[community:c:marvel:Amazing Fantasy Vol 1 15|Amazing Fantasy Vol. 1 #15]]'', the comic featuring the first appearance of Spider-Man, cover-dated August 10, 1962.
*Parker is a fan of the indie rock bands [[Alt-J]] and [[Led Zeppelin]] listening to the former's song "Left Hand Free" prior to meeting Tony Stark and mentioning his love for the latter whilst forming the [[Spider-Man Suit|Upgraded Suit]] and listening to AC/DC.
*Parker is a ''{{WPS|Star Wars}}'' fan and a {{WPS|Lego}} collector. Parker has Star Wars action figures and Lego models of the {{WPS|Death Star}}, an {{WPS|X-Wing fighter}}, and an {{WPS|Walker (Star Wars)#All Terrain Armored Transport (AT-AT)|AT-AT Walker}}. He also referenced ''{{WPS|The Empire Strikes Back}}'' during the [[Battle at Leipzig-Halle Airport]].
**Despite this, at the time [[Tom Holland]] claimed to not be a big ''Star Wars'' fan and had not seen {{WPS|Star Wars (film)|the}} {{WPS|The Empire Strikes Back|original}} {{WPS|Return of the Jedi|trilogy}}, though he did enjoy ''{{WPS|Star Wars: The Force Awakens}}'' and ''{{WPS|Rogue One}}'', as well as {{WPS|Star Wars: Episode I – The Phantom Menace|the}} {{WPS|Star Wars: Episode II – Attack of the Clones|prequel}} {{WPS|Star Wars: Episode III – Revenge of the Sith|trilogy}} when he was a child.<ref>[http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/spider-man-star-tom-holland-admits-hes-never-seen-empire-strikes-back-993009 'Spider-Man' Star Tom Holland Admits He's Never Seen 'Empire Strikes Back']</ref>
*Parker is a fan of the [[New York Mets]].
*Parker's school locker is #1184.
*Spider-Man is one of three superheroes who defeated the main antagonist of their first standalone movie without any assistance, the other two being [[Hulk]] and [[Ant-Man]].
*Spider-Man is the second superhero to star in two solo films in the same [[Phase Three|phase]], with the first being [[Iron Man]].
*Parker began his sophomore year of high school in [[2016]], meaning he was originally set to graduate in [[2019]] prior to the [[Snap]]. Following the [[Blip]], he was set to graduate in [[2025]] due to everyone having to repeat his junior year of high school, before everyone's memories of him were erased and forcing him to earn his GED.
*In the comics, a version inspired of MCU Spider-Man appeared in ''Spider-Verse #3'' and in ''Spider-Geddon'' #5 as part of the Spider-Army assembled to fight the Inheritors led by the Earth-616's Spider-Man.
*Spider-Man is listed as one of the default names on ''[[The Avengers: Skrull Takedown]]'''s high score screen.

==Behind the Scenes==
*Spider-Man was first indirectly referenced in an alternate version of the [[List of Post-credits Scenes|post-credits scene]] for ''[[Iron Man (film)|Iron Man]]'', in which [[Nick Fury]] mentioned to [[Tony Stark]] about "radioactive bug bites" on the "bigger universe" he has become part. This version ultimately went unused from the finished film, likely because [[Sony Pictures Entertainment]] owns the film rights of Spider-Man.<ref>[https://twitter.com/DiscussingFilm/status/1172782239173636097 DiscussingFilm on Twitter - September 14, 2019]</ref>
*[[Joss Whedon]] wanted to include Spider-Man at the end of ''[[Avengers: Age of Ultron]]'', but was unable to do so because the deal with [[Sony Pictures Entertainment]] had yet to be completed during filming.<ref>[https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/joss-whedon-avengers-age-ultron-793502 Joss Whedon on Fighting With Marvel Over 'Avengers: Age of Ultron': "It Got Really, Really Unpleasant"]</ref>
*[[Tom Holland]] made audition tapes together with [[Jon Bernthal]] while filming ''{{WPS|Pilgrimage (2015 film)|Pilgrimage}}'', both landing their roles of Peter Parker and [[Frank Castle]] respectively.<ref>[http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/movies/exclusive-bernthal-holland-teamed-marvel-auditions-article-1.2560381 EXCLUSIVE: Jon Bernthal and Tom Holland made audition tapes together to land The Punisher and Spider-Man roles]</ref>
*[[Tom Holland]] learned that he had been cast as Spider-Man on {{WPS|Instagram}}: ''"I was actually having a really bad day, and I found out on Instagram. I was in my bed, I was scrolling through Instagram, and Marvel had posted a photo of Spider-Man. It said, 'Go to our website, and find out who it is'. I opened the screen, and then it said my name, and I went nuts."''<ref>[http://www.digitalspy.com/movies/spider-man/news/a777288/tom-holland-found-out-about-spider-man-casting-on-instagram/ Tom Holland found out about his Spider-Man casting on Instagram]</ref>
*During his audition, Tom Holland mentioned that [[Robert Downey Jr.]] gave him advice, saying "''Listen, I remember my screen test for Iron Man. I remember how terrified I was. Just think of it as an audition. It's nothing too scary. If you get it wrong, we'll just start again. No pressure.''."
*[[Max Favreau]], the son of [[Jon Favreau]], had a role as an "Expo Kid" in ''[[Iron Man 2]]'' which was later retconned as a young Peter Parker.
**In an interview with the {{WPS|Huffington Post}}, Holland confirmed that the child that [[Iron Man]] rescues from the [[Hammer Drones]] in ''[[Iron Man 2]]'' was, in fact, Peter Parker after "literally" having conversation with [[Marvel Studios]] President [[Kevin Feige]] "only 20 minutes ago." [[Jon Watts]] revealed in an interview with {{WPS|Uproxx}} that the boy retroactively revealed to be Parker was portrayed by [[Jon Favreau]]'s son, [[Max Favreau]].<ref name="IM2C">[http://ew.com/movies/2017/06/27/spider-man-homecoming-director-peter-parker-iron-man-2-cameo Spider-Man: Homecoming director confirms Peter Parker's Iron Man 2 cameo]</ref>
*Spider-Man in the [[Marvel Cinematic Universe]] is the sixth live-action incarnation of the character, following incarnations portrayed by {{WPS|Spidey Super Stories|Danny Seagren}}, {{WPS|Nicholas Hammond}}, {{WPS|Spider-Man (Japanese TV series)|Shinji Tôdô}}, [[Tobey Maguire]] and [[Andrew Garfield]].
**Unlike previous incarnations, this Spider-Man's agility and athleticism were performed by actor Tom Holland due to his history in dance and gymnastics, thereby allowing a majority of the stunts to be produced practically and without CGI.
*Tom Holland mentioned that he has signed on for three Spider-Man movies and three other Marvel films, bringing a total of six films in his contract.
*{{WPS|Asa Butterfield}}, {{WPS|Charlie Rowe}}, {{WPS|Judah Lewis}}, [[Matt Lintz]] and {{WPS|Charlie Plummer}} were the final contenders for Spider-Man with Rowe being the runner-up for the role. Lintz would later be cast as [[Bruno Carrelli]] in ''[[Ms. Marvel (TV series)|Ms. Marvel]]''.
*In ''[[Captain America: Civil War]]'', Spider-Man kicks but never punches. Holland noted it was a conscious decision to emphasize Parker's age: "''Every decision we make on set is based off, 'How would a kid react in this situation?' so every fight scene we have is designed in a way that's almost child-friendly, so he never actually punches anyone. It's all done [by him] kind of by accident.''"<ref>[http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/spider-man-homecoming-tom-holland-doesnt-punch-anyone-945609 THR: Tom Holland Explains Why His Spider-Man "Never Actually Punches Anyone"]</ref>
**Ironically, Spider-Man himself never punched any bad guys he fought against in the {{WPS|Spider-Man: The Animated Series|original animated TV series}}.
*In the Italian dubbing of the ''[[Iron Fist (TV series)|Iron Fist]]'' episode ''[[Eight Diagram Dragon Palm]]'', [[Ward Meachum]] mentions Spider-Man when he compares [[Danny Rand]]'s scaling of a building, instead of [[Daredevil]].<ref>[https://vimeo.com/208961618 Vimeo: Spider-Man reference in the Italian dubbing of Iron Fist]</ref>{{Ref|IF104}}
*Spider-Man is mentioned in the [[Wu-Tang Clan]] song "{{WPS|Protect Ya Neck}}," which is featured in ''[[The Defenders]]'' episode ''[[The Defenders (episode)|The Defenders]]''.{{Ref|TD108}}
*This version of Parker served as one of the inspirations for one of the Spider-Men featured in the {{WPS|Sony Pictures Animation}} film ''{{WPS|Spider-Man: Into the Spider-Verse}}''.<ref>[https://www.fandango.com/movie-news/interview-into-the-spider-verse-producers-phil-lord-and-chris-miller-talk-spider-man-stan-lee-and-reinventing-the-comic-book-movie-753510 Interview: 'Into the Spider-Verse' Producers Phil Lord and Chris Miller Talk Spider-Man, Stan Lee and Reinventing the Comic Book Movie]</ref> There were also plans to include Holland's Spider-Man in an scene which would have featured him alongside Maguire's and Garfield's versions of the character, but the scene was scrapped due to fears it would have been far too convoluted.<ref>[https://www.flickeringmyth.com/2019/01/spider-man-into-the-spider-verse-almost-featured-tobey-maguire-andrew-garfield-and-tom-holland/ Spider-Man: Into the Spider-Verse almost featured Tobey Maguire, Andrew Garfield and Tom Holland]</ref> Holland's Spider-Man would have appeared at a train station where he would have greeted Miles Morales while walking through the background as an {{WPS|Easter egg (media)|Easter egg}}, but the scene was cut.<ref>[https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/06/tom-holland-spider-man-cameo-miles-morales Tom Holland Met Miles Morales in Cut Spider-Man: Into the Spider-Verse Cameo]</ref>
*''[[The Falcon and The Winter Soldier]]'' showrunner [[Malcolm Spellman]] stated in an interview with ''{{WPS|Inverse (website)|Inverse}}'' that there were plans to include Spider-Man in the [[The Falcon and The Winter Soldier/Season One|first season]] finale "[[One World, One People]]", as the episode takes place in [[New York City]], but [[Kevin Feige]] convinced him to not include Spidey because he didn't belong to the story in an organic way.<ref>[https://www.inverse.com/entertainment/falcon-the-winter-soldier-showrunner-talks-mcu-cameos-marvels-steve-rogers-mystery THE FALCON AND THE WINTER SOLDIER WRITER HAS BAD NEWS FOR STEVE ROGERS FANS]</ref>
*[[Marvin Ross]], [[Holland Diaz]], [[Danny Downey]], [[David Elson]], [[Alrik Kreemke]], [[Chris Silcox]], [[Christian Peden]], [[Luke Scott]], [[Greg Townley]] and [[John Flanagan]] were stunt doubles for [[Tom Holland]] in the role of Spider-Man.
**Diaz and Elson were both stunt doubles for previous cinematic incarnations of Spider-Man. Diaz doubled for [[Tobey Maguire]] in ''{{WPS|Spider-Man 3}}'' and Elson doubled for [[Andrew Garfield]] in ''{{WPS|The Amazing Spider-Man (2012 film)|The Amazing Spider-Man}}''.
*[[Ian Kyle Findley]], [[Freddy Parkington]], and [[Shane Hibbard]] were stand-ins for [[Tom Holland]] in the role of Spider-Man.
*Spider-Man, [[T'Challa|Black Panther]], and [[Black Widow]] are the only characters in the [[Marvel Cinematic Universe]] to receive a solo movie following their debut.
*Spider-Man is one of the three main protagonists who are able to defeat the main antagonist without assistance in the ''MCU'', the others being the [[Hulk]], [[Ant-Man]],  and [[Deadpool]] and [[Wolverine]] in all of their titular films. So far, he has been the only one to do it more than once. 
*This version of the character is featured in the post-credit scene of ''{{WPS|Venom: Let There Be Carnage}}'' which ties into the ending of ''[[Spider-Man: Far From Home]]''.{{Ref|VLTBC}}
**He was also mentioned in the post-credit scene of ''{{WPS|Morbius (film)|Morbius}}'' which ties into the ending of ''[[Spider-Man: No Way Home]]''.<ref>As depicted in the film ''{{WPS|Morbius (film)|Morbius}}''</ref>
*This version of Spider-Man is mentioned in the {{WPS|Sony Pictures Animation}} film ''{{WPS|Spider-Man: Across the Spider-Verse}}''.<ref>As depicted in the film ''{{WPS|Spider-Man: Across the Spider-Verse}}''</ref> Co-director {{WPS|Kemp Powers}} later clarified in an interview with SFX, however, that Miguel O'Hara's mention of Spider-Man was merely a reference to ''[[Spider-Man: No Way Home]]'' that {{WPS|Phil Lord and Christopher Miller}} came up with as a tongue-in-cheek joke acknowledging the [[w:c:marvel:Spider-Man|Spider-Man]] character's history.<ref>[https://www.digitalspy.com/movies/a43884356/spider-man-across-spiderverse-mcu-crossover/ Spider-Man: Across the Spider-Verse director addresses MCU crossover]</ref>

